<br>
I broke out the ole chalkboard today and generated some information of possible interest to those spirits of the cloth.<br>
<br>
In Theology we understand that &quot;Mana&quot; is a measure of thine wisdom of spirit and faith in thine God. Meaning - If thee keep casting, faith becomes stronger, thus increasing experience and strengthened bond.  In turn, thine faith, art channeled from thine God, and converted into a blessing.  This conversion of faith, into a more commercially usable substance, is called Alteration.  This conversion is done via &quot;spells,&quot; which is a term for the blessings of your work. <br>
<br>
These blessings lead into the mastery of craft of &quot;Clerics.&quot;  The Clerics use the alterations to cure, heal, bind, fear, and even imbue stones!  There are some spells that were crafted by men that loved to hear their own words, whom saw Ministry as a poetic artform. Later these Ministers became politicians, but that is a whole different story.  Since Norrath has become corrupted, Clerics have been asked to guide adventurers and protect them on their travels.  Which lead to shortening the faith conversioning system.  What we have in our spellbooks today are a mix of some of the pieces of Ministry artwork, but if carefully studied we can see that their place can be in a museum rather than our spellbooks. We also know of the one to three word blessings that are extremely easy to cast.  A true Cleric does not need an Ego boost to prove his faith in his God, as his relation to spirituality he finds plenty of pleasure beyond superfituality of Self Esteem.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
First off - We'll compare the Mana use per time<br>
<br>
M / Hp = MpHp (Mana divided by heal point = Mana per Heal point)<br>
<br>
The lower the number, the less mana used for heal<br>
<br>
For example .25 means 4 mana for 16 points of healing / .5 means 2 mana = 4 Heal Points<br>
<br>
<br>
