Printed this one out to look at more (after adding Supernal Remedy Calcs).  Will probably experiment a little with some of this information to see if I can get more mana effective (shh...do not tell my lab rats...errm...group/raid members).  To take what you have said one step further though (to those of you who think this is geeky now...run fast and far...it is gonna get MUCH worse...)  <br>
<br>
Many of the comments you are getting are directed at the factors not addressed here.  The calcs kinda bothered me intuitively, because it did not make sense relative to how I often play and I like to think I am a decent healer.  Reason why it bothered me is intuitively, I would say spam heals are often (not always) more efficient.  At a group level, how many times have you thrown a CH and within 2 seconds, the shammy has slowed the Mob...lol  At the level of having multiple clerics healing like on a raid, CH chains are (often...not always) clunky with a higher risk of failure than many clerics spam healing (I know some people will not agree with me on this, but, please go try and run an effective CH chain on a pickup raid before you throw rocks at me on this one...and if you have and still disagree with me...I will give up on Rodcet Nife and come worship at YOUR feet to teach me how to do this better).<br>
<br>
What you are essentially doing is calculating average (mean) values for heals.  If the amount of damage being done is fixed, this would be all the information you would ever need to be efficient all the time.  However, damage done by Mobs is a chance of being hit and then a random amount of damage, so the amount of healing you need at any point in time is a variable with an expected mean AND a variance.  Assuming the cleric is competent, death still occurs from variances in damage from the Mob over what the expected value.  Something many people do not get and have a life crisis when somebody dies...the variance can kill yah...no matter what you do...it will happen when you are on the tail end of the damage distribution curve.<br>
<br>
In many cases, the goal is not to be mana efficient, it is to keep a catastrophic event from occuring (wipe of raid) with some lesser considerations (keep individuals from dying...though some raids, people are gonna die *shrugs*) using a fixed resource (mana).  In other words, as long as you do not run out of mana, being efficient is not important.  Once you factor in all these extra variables that interact, you have a level of complexity in calculation that means the human ability to make judgements and decisions based on limited information and time becomes critical.  Which is what makes being a cleric fun (at least for me).<br>
